  <p style="color:black">All across the United States, colleges are disappearing.</p>

  <p style="color:black">As a result, the lives of students and their families have been plunged into unexpected crisis. A <i>Chronicle</i> analysis of federal data shows that, in the last five years, about half a million students have been displaced by college closures, which together shuttered more than 1,200 campuses.</p>

  <p style="color:black">Thatâ€™s an average of 20 campus closures per month. Many of those affected are working adults living paycheck to paycheck, who carried hopes that college would be their path to the middle class.</p>

  <p style="color:black">Most are age 25 or older. About one in four are at least 35 years old.</p>

  <p style="color:black">â€œOne class left,â€ Lisa La More wrote on Facebook last month, after the for-profit college she attended, the Art Institute of Californiaâ€™s San Diego campus, shut down. â€œLess than 3 weeks from my BS in Graphic and Web. 6 years of my life WASTED. I am 48 years old, with teenage kids. What am I supposed to do now?â€</p>


  <p style="color:black">College closures donâ€™t just disproportionately hurt older students. They have severely hit low-income students, too: Nearly 70 percent of undergraduates at closed campuses received need-based Pell Grants. Black and Hispanic students also bear the brunt. About 57 percent of displaced students are racial minorities.</p>


  <p style="color:black">Most of the closures have one thing in common: It was a for-profit college that shut down. Among the more than 1,230 campuses that closed, 88 percent were operated by for-profit colleges. For-profit colleges represent only about one-tenth of U.S. college enrollment, but they account for nearly 85 percent of students displaced by closures in the last five years, according to <i>The Chronicleâ€™</i>s analysis. That adds up to roughly 450,000 displaced for-profit college students.</p>

  <p style="color:black">In the last six months, the for-profit college implosions have included Vatterott College, which boasted 15 campuses across the Midwest; Alabama-based Education Corporation of America, which once had 70 campuses nationwide; and Dream Center Education Holdings, which shut down 41 for-profit campuses operating as either the Art Institutes or Argosy University.</p>

  <p style="color:black">Not every displaced student drops out of school entirely. Some colleges might shutter a campus but allow students to continue their education through online courses. But in those instances, the students are not receiving the program they signed up for, on the terms that they wanted.</p>

  <p style="color:black">When a college fully goes out of business, there is no easy fix for the people caught in the crossfire. Closures can be both traumatic and financially ruinous for students â€” many of whom are single parents like La More. La More told <i>The Chronicle</i> that she had completed most of her final class, which required students to put together a full-scale rebranding campaign for a make-believe client. The project was an opportunity for students to demonstrate the skills they had accumulated through years of study.</p>

  <p style="color:black">La More completed every part of the branding campaign except one: a budget for how much to spend on billboards and business cards. The San Diego campus closed before she could complete the budget plan. There were two and a half weeks left in the academic term.</p>

  <h2>A Surge in Closures</h2>

  <p style="color:black">The increased frequency of for-profit campus closures is a problem that the Trump administration inherited. The number of shuttered colleges per year surged from 50 in 2009 to a peak of 448 in 2016. Around 175 closures occurred in each of the past two years.</p>

  <p style="color:black">The industryâ€™s trade group, Career Education Colleges and Universities, acknowledges that it is a problem that so many college students are being displaced by closures.</p>

  <p style="color:black">But for the most part, the groupâ€™s chief executive, Steve Gunderson, doesnâ€™t think for-profit colleges themselves are to blame. The industryâ€™s reputation and its financial footing, he said, were damaged by the Obama administration, which put in place a set of stricter regulations designed to protect students.</p>

  <p style="color:black">The previous administration also revoked an accreditor seen as overly lenient on for-profit colleges, while citing specific examples of for-profitsâ€™ misbehavior to justify its tougher stance.</p>

  <p style="color:black">â€œYou canâ€™t declare war on a sector without having a huge negative impact,â€ Gunderson said. Students, he argued, end up getting hurt in the process.</p>

  <p style="color:black">U.S. Sen. Dick Durbin, an Illinois Democrat, lays the blame for recent for-profit college closures squarely at the feet of the industry. At a House appropriations subcommittee hearing last month, Durbin rattled off the names of for-profits that had closed within the last few months. â€œThe collapse of these schools tells you theyâ€™re not even good economic and financial models,â€ said Durbin, who has pushed for stricter oversight of the industry. â€œThey take all the money they can, and then run for the border.â€</p>

  <p style="color:black">Education Secretary Betsy DeVos has staffed her department with former for-profit college executives, and the Trump administration has scaled back oversight of these institutions. DeVos allowed Dream Center â€” which had no higher-education experience â€” to purchase the Art Institute and Argosy campuses in 2017. It was a controversial decision, as the Obama administration had previously rejected Dream Centerâ€™s attempt to buy a different for-profit college chain.</p>

  <p style="color:black">In addition to allowing unproven, inexperienced operators like Dream Center to run for-profit systems, DeVosâ€™s Education Department has also scaled back efforts to help the students displaced by for-profit failures. A key example is what happens to those studentsâ€™ loan debt. Under a decades-old federal law, students who are attending a college that closes (or who withdraw shortly before the college shuts down) are entitled to have their federal loans forgiven. The logic is simple: Students borrowed the money with the intention of earning a specific degree, and the college going out of business denied them that opportunity.</p>

  <p style="color:black">The Obama administration studied how well that law was working. It found evidence that many students who attended closed colleges had neither moved on to study elsewhere nor asked for loan forgiveness. In all likelihood, these students had simply given up on college and were carrying debt they didnâ€™t have to.</p>

  <p style="color:black">So the Obama administration created an â€œautomatic closed school dischargeâ€ for these students. Three years after a college closes, if a student isnâ€™t using those credits, the loans automatically go away. The provision was part of a regulatory package known as â€œborrower defense to repayment,â€ released in the waning months of the Obama presidency.</p>

  <p style="color:black">DeVos repeatedly delayed implementing the borrower-defense regulations â€” a judge in September called those delays â€œarbitrary and capricious,â€ and ordered the rules to immediately take effect.</p>

  <p style="color:black">In November, a consumer group sued, alleging that the Education Department was still dragging its feet in processing automatic discharges. Since that lawsuit, the department has picked up the pace â€“ discharging more than $158 million in loans (affecting 15,000 borrowers).</p>

  <p style="color:black">But at the same time, the Trump administration has been working on its own proposed rewrite of the borrower-defense regulations. An early version of that plan eliminated automatic closed-school discharges, and it sought to drastically reduce the number of students who would qualify for closed-school loan forgiveness if they asked for it.</p>

  <p style="color:black">The administrationâ€™s proposal was to deny discharges to students from closed colleges that offered â€œteach-outs,â€ which are an alternate pathway for students to finish their programs and graduate.</p>

  <p style="color:black">Some colleges have shut down without arranging teach-outs. At the colleges that do provide them, the quality varies. In the worst cases, students end up at a transfer college that neglects them or demands additional money. In that scenario, the quality of instruction can deteriorate rapidly as employees leave and equipment isnâ€™t maintained.</p>

  <h2>â€˜I Was Angryâ€™</h2>

  <p style="color:black">For example, Dream Centerâ€™s Art Institutes shut down a dozen locations in December, including the Illinois Institute of Art in Schaumburg, where Natalie Kalupski was studying graphic design.   <p style="color:black">In recent months, the Trump administration said it was no longer planning to deny loan forgiveness based on the availability of teach-outs.   <p style="color:black">Whatever the department decides could ultimately affect lots of students at nonprofit colleges too.   <p style="color:black">For-profit college closures can be sudden. Students might receive only a couple of days of advance notice, or maybe no notice at all.</p>

  <p style="color:black">Students at Harrison College â€” a small, Indianapolis-based for-profit chain that closed in September â€” found out what was happening from social media and their local TV news.   <p style="color:black">Webb said he sees a common thread in the multiple campus-closure cases he has handled, which tend to affect older, nontraditional students who have a limited window of time to earn a degree.</p>

  <p style="color:black">â€œThe rug is pulled out from under them, and they canâ€™t survive it,â€ he said. â€œThat window may not ever open again. They may be too old. The kids may be growing up.â€</p>

  <p style="color:black">In theory, students who are unsure about what to do have the help of their state government, the federal government, and college accreditors â€” the so-called regulatory triad of higher-education oversight.   <p style="color:black">After a closure, in the heat of the moment, itâ€™s easy for students to make a bad decision, or to act without a complete understanding of their options. Many are desperate for a path that will still allow them to graduate.</p>

  <p style="color:black">When Harrison College closed, records obtained by <i>The Chronicle</i> through a public-records request show that the state of Indiana received multiple emails from colleges interested in signing up the displaced students.   <p style="color:black">Even when a student at a dying college notices the warning signs, there are many reasons why students might stay enrolled.
